“Why she be yellin’ so much?”
Rico Nasty is known for screaming, yelling, and generally being loud with her music, much to the annoyance of her haters

I don’t need your opinion (I don’t need it, bitch)
 Do what I fuckin’ want (Do what I fuckin’ want)
Sugar Trap!

This refers to her 2016 release “Sugar Trap”, and her subsequent 2017 release “Sugar Trap 2”.

The term “sugar trap” describes the definitive sound that Rico pioneered and has quickly become the face of. Sugar trap blends sweet, melodic “bubblegum-type” beats along with elements of hardcore trap, described in her Spotify bio as “blending bubblegum and bullets”.

“You rap about a Audi too much” (Shut the fuck up)
 Because my Audi paid off, bitch, hush! (Shut the fuck up!)

Audis are nothing new to Rico Nasty, as she owns two of them. She owns a green one and a red one, but has mentioned the red one more in her songs. Rico mentions the red Audi in her 2017 song “Poppin”, rapping,


In an Audi going fast, you behind us

I said I’m in a red Audi, bitches fruit punchin'


She also brings it up in another 2017 song titled “Rojo”,

I’m in a four door, four O’s (four O’s, yeah)
Red car, Rojo (Rojo)

In the official Rojo music video, the red Audi is seen, and Rico even went as far as featuring it on the cover art. She stated that it was the first car she bought with her own money.

Rico mentions Audis in more songs too, such as Blue and AR-15. Maybe she does rap about an Audi too much, but that’s okay because Rico is proud of her success (and loves her Audis).

annotations: Geekin’ in the mentions

“Mentions” could refer to twitter mentions, or using the ‘@’ symbol and someone’s username to get their attention. Twitter is full of a lot of haters who try to directly pick fights with musicians and celebrities, but it seems Rico just laughs them off as they don’t seem to bother her.

No more Happy Meals, just champagne cheers
 I used to not have fans, now I fill up fields

She is painting the picture of the rags to riches story. Every artist has a come up story and this is Rico’s. Now that she is getting and seeing money she can afford more than just Mcdonalds food. She also mentions her fan base increased.

No Aminé, we reel in
 Any bitches fishin’ and seekin’ out for attention

This is a nod to Aminé’s 2018 hit “REEL IT IN,” from his “EPLPMixtapeAlbum” ONEPOINTFIVE. On the chorus, he raps:

Reel it in (Woo)
I got the bag, tell a friend (Hoo)
She got some ass, bring it in (Ayy)
Bitch, I’m the news, CNN, yeah

“Fishing for compliments” is a phrase used to describe someone criticizing themselves so that other people will praise them, thus “seekin' out for attention.” Rico Nasty uses a wordplay on “fishin'” as the literal meaning of “reel in” is to pull in a fish that is caught on a hook by turning the reel of a fishing rod.

Aminé has also name-dropped Rico on his 2018 song “DAPPERDAN”:

I’m nasty like I’m Rico

Moreover, on his 2020 song “Burden,” he alludes to Rico’s aggressive rapping style :

Screamin' like I’m Rico

The two rappers have also collaborated before on Aminé’s 2018 song “SUGARPARENTS” and appeared on an episode of Spotify’s Butt Dial podcast in July 2020.



Rico Nasty and Aminé pictured together
Niggas said I’m actin’ different since I got a deal

Rico Nasty signed a deal by Atlantic Records in 2018 shortly after she shared the album art and release date of her debut album, Nasty.

This may be referring to her being more motivated by the increase of money.
Please don’t make me have to smack a bitch

Nasty is alluding to one of her breakout singles entitled “Smack A Bitch” released in early 2018. The lyrics between both are similar with the chorus of “Smack A Bitch” being:

Smack a bitch today
Thank God I ain’t have to smack a bitch today

While Juice was freestyling, his friend kept saying “goggles, goggles, google” Then Juice said “Tell the fuck niggas leave me alone”. This was said because his friend wouldn’t stop saying “goggles”.
W, W, how can I lose?

Juice makes use of the repetition of the letter ‘W'—an alternate term for 'win'—to allude to the amount of positive outcomes that have surpassed within his career.

He made similar use of repetition in his unreleased track “Vlone Thugs,” where he rapped:

W, W, W, W, W, huh, repetition
I cannot stop winning, had to work for it, wasn’t given

I pull up on that Fanta and that Sprite
 So I told that Pepsi to leave me ’lone

Within this segment of the freestyle, Juice is shown a can of Pepsi soda, in which he spits these lines regarding the object, making reference to two other soda brands, Fanta and Sprite.

Juice also mentions that he “pours up"—the act of pouring codeine and promethazine into a soda to concoct the opiate, lean. Fanta and Sprite are the most common soda beverages that are used within the creation of lean.



Pictured: a soda can of Pepsi.
[Verse 11: Juice WRLD]

Verse eleven to sixteen use the same Hit-Boy-produced instrumental as Juice’s unreleased collaboration with G Herbo, titled “Pop It.” It is thought that the track was recorded in the same studio session as this freestyle.
Jimmy Choo, my shoe, uh

Jimmy Choo is a British luxury fashion brand that specializes in accessories such as shoes, hence Juice referring to it. The brand was founded in 1996 in London and was made eponymous by Malaysian fashion designer Jimmy Choo.



Juice references Jimmy Choo in 2018’s taken down track “Demon Love”, where he raps:

She gon' act like Satan in those Jimmy Choo’s
I’m a A&R but got flows, nigga

The artists and repertoire (A&R) division is essentially a division within record labels to scout out talented artists. An A&R has to analyze and search for talented artists who have potential and can make a name for themselves in the industry.

Dazz claims that even though is one of the A&R scouts within a record label, he still has flows and can rap smoothly.
That was a green lighter, that wasn’t a BIC, though

In the freestyle at this point, Juice was shown a green lighter of unknown brand. Juice claims that it isn’t a BIC Lighter – an American brand that specializes in numerous types of lighters.



Pictured: A BIC lighter.
I’m ballin’ out, like the Celtics

The Boston Celtics are an NBA team based in Boston, Massachusetts. The franchise have won 17 NBA championships, which is the most in history alongside their archrivals, who are the Los Angeles Lakers.
VVS cold like it’s sleigh weather

VVS is short for “very, very, slightly“ and refers to the clarity of a diamond. VVS diamonds have extremely slight inclusions and imperfections, making them worth lots of money.

Additionally, diamonds are known to feel cold when touched, and Juice relates it to cold or snowy weather, in which a person would ride on a sleigh or sled.

Juice has used this relation numerous times in his music, such as on his unreleased track “Arctic Tundra,“ where he sings and relates diamonds to the titular biome:

My VVS cold, like an arctic tundra

annotations: If it ain’t more than a thousand, I won’t put it on my feet, bitch

Seeing as the previous line mentions “Doc Marten[s],” this line is most likely hyperbolic in nature. Dr. Marten shoes typically range from $100.00 to $200.00 in price, and only special hand-painted or out-of-production Docs can set you back over a thousand dollars. From this one can infer Rico is not entirely opposed to putting articles of clothing on her feet if they do not cost an exorbitant price, but rather stating her expensive tastes.

Bloody Mary on my toes
 Every time I pop out, it get scary for you hoes

Bloody Mary could both refer to a nail polish color, but also to the ghost of a women, who will appear when you say her name in front of the mirror three times. The story differs depending on who is telling it, but Megan here highlights the element of surprise and how every time she puts out new music other people are afraid of being roasted or dropping off the charts.
Red bottom on my feet
Red bottoms – as in red soles, it’s a distinctive element of Christian Louboutin shoes (as of now they have exclusive rights to the red soles) which are often considered a mark of wealth.
Jewelry so cold, gave these broke bitches goosebumps

Jewelry is often referred to as ice and of course ice is cold. In the cold, people often get goosebumps, which is little dots/pimples on their skin. People also get goosebumps when they are scared.



Goosebumps is also a popular franchise based on children and teen’s horror books by R.L. Stine. These books and the Fear Street series, also by R.L. Stine, were very popular in the 90’s.
Only time my buttons pushed is when I’m pressin’ on my keys

Keys here means the keys of a keyboard instrument, most likely a piano. Megan played the piano on Megan’s Piano.

Having your buttons pushed usually means having something bother you emotionally or mentally. So Megan is saying that nothing can bother her/get to her.
Lookin’ for a bitch to play with, then you better Ask Jeeves

Ask Jeeves is a question and answer website, established in 1996 by Garrett Gruener and David Warthen in Berkeley, California.



Pictured: Ask Jeeves' website.

In terms of Megan’s boundaries, she expresses her disdain for an individual, a potential enemy in her case. “Ask Jeeves” literally implies her disinterest in finding drama, also Megan asserts them to someone else to beef with.
Zombie-ass bitch (Yeah, yeah), nigga gave me brain for dinner (Yummy)

The fictional monster the Zombie is known for feasting on the brains of humans. Brain is also slang for oral sex. Rico makes a comedic play on words by comparing herself to a Zombie because she gets ‘brain’ for dinner (oral sex).
Shout out Megan the hottie (Let’s go), yeah, I be the hottest topic (Rico)

Hot Topic is a store known for its alternative, counter-culture clothing and accessories. Rico references it to tie into the song’s horror-core themes while making it known that she is rising in popularity and prominence (a hot topic).
White Ghost rollin’ through the hood, look like Klu Klux

Megan conveys her wealth by mentioning white supremacists, right-wing terrorists, and a hate group, The Ku Klux Klan. The group, —commonly known as KKK or the Klan,— targets those who are Jews, Latinos, and Asians but that are primarily African Americans.

However, although most African Americans have a deep detestation over the group. Megan, in these lines, compares the group’s undesirable attire in order to address the spec of her Rolls Royce Ghost.



Pictured: KKK’s whole attire.

Say my name like Candyman, and bitch, you know I’m there
 These hoes wish they saw me when they lookin’ in the mirror

Megan compares herself to the character in the 1992 horror movie, Candyman in terms of her willingness to engage in what appears to be violence as displayed throughout the song.

Candyman depicts an African-American man named Candyman being brutally murdered for having an illicit love affair with a white lady. After his death, he returns as a legend due to the consequence of his study into urban legends, which led to reports of a fictional serial murderer known as Candyman. In the film, Candyman would appear anywhere and slay anyone when summoned five times in front of a mirror. Megan plays on this, boasting her physical appearance, stating that “hoes” wish they could see her reflection in the mirror.

annotations: You keep talkin’ that shit, I’ll build a skate park in your hood

In case you didn’t know, Weezy has a low tolerance for bullshit.

Nowadays, Wayne is skating and many people are giving him a hard time saying he’s fake and that he’s changed. Wayne doesn’t care what these people imply, and to prove his point, he’s willing to bring his skating right to their faces to show it.
Street sweeper, make a nigga bite the dust

Street sweeper is slang for a type of shotgun, and bite the dust is a phrase which means to die. Weezy is implying here that he will use his shotgun to kill any nigga that tries him.

Also note the wordplay, “sweeper” and “dust”.
Uh, I don’t need light, my bitch light enough

You could interpret this in many ways.


Light could be referrring to pigmentation since Wayne is a dark individual, and by having a light bitch he balances out the lighting.
The light is also claimed to be an indicator of death, and people go to the light when they die.
The light could refer to to a figurative light as in a path, a way of righteousness through which one finds happiness.



Regardless of the intention, Wayne is claiming he doesn’t need light and casually dismisses the notion and displays confidence by bragging about how he has a light bitch which is enough.
I’m homeless, bum rush em

Wordplay.

People whom are homeless are often called bums, so since Wayne is claiming he’s a homeless, he has to bum rush his enemies.
Upside down, her blood rushing

When someone is upside down, they begin to feel pressure in their face as all the blood rushes towards their head. Weezy implies that the sex position is upside down which means her blood will be rushing.

Also blood rushing is a sign of adrenaline, or the heart beating faster in excitement so he could be implying that that the sex is so good it’s making the girl extremely excited. Considering Wayne’s status, this is no shocking accomplishment.
Y’all Must Have Forgot, Roy Jones

It’s not a common opinion that YMCMB is a trashy label with untalented rappers.

Jae Millz is responding to this by reminding us he has the crew of the year, and also uses a clever allusion to the track “Y'all Must’ve Forgot” by Roy Jones Jr.

Millz also acknowledges YMCMB haters again on his track Hearing Voices
